[2] Fear fireblight will kill orchard business
Date: Thu 17 May 2007
Source: Adelaide Now [edited]
<http://www.news.com.au/adelaidenow/story/0,22606,21744887-2682,00.html>

Michael Nicol fears his family's 5-generation apple growing business in the
Adelaide Hills will be wiped out by the entry of New Zealand apples into
the country. He believes the arrival of NZ apples on to Australian fruit
shop shelves within 2 years will bring with it the dreaded fireblight, a
[bacterial disease] described as the foot and mouth disease of the apple
and pear industry. "I think the odds are very high that we will get
fireblight and that it will infect our industry. I would think a minimum of
30 and up to 50 per cent of growers would be forced out by the disease."
Quarantine authorities Biosecurity Australia and AQIS have told the Senate
rural committee there is a very low risk fireblight will come into
Australia if the importation goes ahead as they recommended in March
[2007]. But last week [7-13 May 2007], the Senate's rural committee told
federal quarantine officers their assessment failed the commonsense test.
Apple and Pear Growers Association of South Australia (SA) general manager,
Trevor Ranford, said the industry would utilise whatever mechanisms to stop
or slow the process, including a legal challenge.
Mr Nicol, president of the Apple and Pears Growers Association of South
Australia, said his apple orchard was at grave risk from fireblight because
it is close to Adelaide and attracts a lot of tourists. He predicted a lot
of orchards would disappear. The SA industry is worth between AUD 40
million and AUD 50 million (USD 30.9-42.4 million) at the farmgate.
[byline: Nigel Austin, rural editor]
