[3] New Zealand apple import decision defies 'commonsense test'
Date: Thu 10 May 2007
Source: Australian Broadcasting Corporation, ABC Rural [edited]
<http://www.abc.net.au/rural/news/content/2006/s1919438.htm>

The head of the Senate's rural affairs committee says a decision to allow
apple imports from New Zealand defies the "commonsense test". Senator Bill
Heffernan made the comments as quarantine officers and unhappy apple
growers gave evidence to the committee last night [9 May 2007].
Quarantine officials admitted there is still a very low risk that the
disease fireblight will enter Australia if imports go ahead. Labor
spokesman for primary industries, senator Kerry O'Brien, says the decision
needs a rethink because officials also admitted there will be no foolproof
test for making sure quarantine protocols have been met.
"What we're told is that it's assumed that fireblight will be in the
orchards, that the time it might get on to the apples to come into this
country later in the growing period would be dealt with by chlorine
dipping," he said. "If we can't be absolutely certain that the dipping has
occurred, then it's possible that one of the aspects of the proposed
protocol would not be met."
--
communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[Fireblight is caused by the bacterium _Erwinia amylovora_. _Erwinia_ is a
plant-pathogenic genus that includes a number of species affecting
vegetable and fruit crops. Fireblight was 1st reported from the state of
New York (USA) and is now widely distributed in northern America, Europe,
small areas of western Asia, and is also endemic to New Zealand. The
disease derived its name from the symptoms of blackening of the leaves as
if they were scorched by fire.
Affected shoots bend forming black hooks, cankers appear on branches and
trunks, and trees invariably die. The bacteria are highly infectious and
are spread by insects (aphids, flies, bees etc), wind, water, and
mechanical means entering the host plant through wounds, often on flowers.
Many varieties of pear and apple trees are susceptible although some less
than others. Only members of the _Rosaceae_ sub-family _Pomoideae_ are
susceptible, including quince, ornamental roses, hawthorn, and firethorn.
_E. amylovora_ was found in _Cotoneaster_ shrubs in both Adelaide and
Melbourne botanical gardens in 1997. The origin of these bacteria is not
known and the infections were successfully eradicated. Local and national
surveys of both orchards and ornamental garden plants did not identify any
further cases.
The importation of plant material, including fruit, from any country with
endemic fireblight would, over time, almost certainly lead to the
establishment of the pathogen in Australia. This would cause enormous costs
to the industry and the national economy for eradication attempts and due
to the loss of Australia's fireblight-free status, which would prohibit
valuable exports to Asian countries including Japan. It would be sheer
madness to prioritise short term political considerations over the long
term future of an important agricultural industry.
